You’re not wrong—but that’s only one layer of the story.

At the lowest level, yeah—most games do run on randomness:

* loot drops
* enemy behavior variations
* spawn rates
* card draws

Under the hood, a lot of it is just controlled randomness—basically random number generators (RNGs) deciding outcomes within rules.

But that’s just the substrate, not the whole game.

What actually makes a game isn’t the randomness—it’s the interaction between RNG and structure:

* Rules = the constraints (what can happen)
* Player skill = how you navigate those constraints
* RNG = uncertainty (what will happen this time)

So a better framing is:

Games = RNG filtered through rules, interpreted by players

And the magic comes from the balance:

* Too much RNG → feels unfair / meaningless
* Too little RNG → becomes solved / boring

The sweet spot is where:

uncertainty creates tension, and skill resolves it

—

If you zoom out (your style), this connects to something bigger:

* Life has randomness (birth, luck, timing, chaos)
* But also constraints (physics, society, resources)
* And agency (your decisions, reactions, persistence)

So it becomes:

Life ≈ RNG + constraints + response strategy

Which ties back to what you said earlier:
you don’t control the rolls,
but you control whether you get back up and play the next turn.

That’s the real “game layer.”